Introduction¶

Hello, the purpose of this following piece is to perform a cursory data based exploration of a competitive discipline that I have been actively following as a hobbyist. To give you context I am a Economist/Computer Scientist with an active interest in esports and as such I decided to leverage my skills, namely my technological prowess alongside with league of legends competitive data that has been provided to use free of use by OraclesElixir, in order to see how my view and understanding of the league meta matches up with the insights that certain portions of the data gives us.

What this piece is not intended to do is make any sort of wide reaching judgements, my belief has always been that statistical data, if properly parsed through by a mind with an understanding of the domain space at a sufficient level, can enhance and or disprove insights but should never be the main tool that an individual utilizes to make qualitative judgements. Rather those should come through the individual utilizing intuition in combination with time and the invaluable skill of introspection. With that being said I hope you enjoy what you read :)

Data Setup¶

In this preliminary section I am simply grabbing the specific subsets of the data that I would like to look at. The reason I do this is the data set comes in as a large dump of the entire competitive season of league of legends games played throughout this year. Not all of that is relevant to me, I set up dataframes that encapsulate the specific parts of the data set I want to look at, segmented by common league abstractions such as leagues, roles, and specific tournaments (worlds).

My thoughts:¶

Here what I was mostly trying to do was understand which leagues played a larger variety of champs. I used the volume of unique champion picks in each role in order to quantify it, however keep in mind the context that the asian leagues have different formats which can affect the level of variety people feel comfortable in bringing out. For example it can safely be said that an average professional will be more willing to take on a degree of risk in their champion pick when they have the safety net of knowing they are playing best of 3's as in LCK versus best of 1's in LCS and LEC where the wrong pick can be more definitively punished.

The first thing that stood out to me is the level of variety coming out of the LCK top lane despite the lower amount of games played. LCK truly live up to their reputation as the home of the top lane, having produced some of the most prodigiously talented top laners throughout all of league history, and as such it only logically follows that there would be a higher degree of creativity coming out from the top lane. Generally that level of willingness to experiment with unique champion picks seems to be present across all roles, as they seem to be willing to pick through a wider range of champions than other regions are. Keep in mind the context that this is all dealing with champion picks in terms of volume and does not necessarily deal with the qualitative variables that can factor into what is good experimentation vs bad experimentation, ie matchup, style of play as a team, etc.

Another interesting thing that immediately jumped out to me was how, despite their large volume of games, the LPL actually does not seem to have the most variety of picks throughout summer. This, in a roundabout way, actually can make sense to me as the LPL has always been a league that very much plays by their own rules. The teams understand the style of play they are best at, in terms of resource allocation, and they very much do stick to their own guns regardless of external pressure from the meta to play a certain way. As such it makes sense to me that over such a large quantity of games the range of being played is lower in comparison to what you would expect

In regards to LCS vs LEC, two leagues with similar formats, one interesting thing that stood out to me was the increased variety in top lane in LEC. This lines up with the state of conventional thinking throughout the summer season, namely that LCS didn't try to utilize the carry potential of top as much as other regions.

My thoughts¶

Immediately my eyes jumped to the LCS pie chart. Considering this graph showed the top five champion picks it was impressive that the four largest pieces of the pie all corresponded to champions that did not have a large carry presence. This is just another indicator that goes to show underutilized the top lane carry threat was in North America and as such it should have come as no surprise when they failed to play catchup to the radically different meta at worlds. If one takes a look at regions like LEC, or even LCK (the region LCS is notoriously influenced by), there is clearly a higher degree of willingness to flex into more primary carry threats as opposed to the LCS which seems highly focused on picking stable minded top lane champions. This definitely had a large part to play in the LCS teams getting baptized by fire, so to speak, on the world stage where there definitely was more of a focus on carry threat from the top lane then they were accustomed to.

Another thing that immediatley jumped out to me here was the Korean infatuation with Kennen, a pick that has historically been utilized to a proficient level by Korean top laners in the past (Smeb being one of the more famous ones that jump to mind), being heavily utilized by the LCK as it seemingly was a top 3 most played champion. Furthermore there was clearly a distinct difference between the value of Renekton when looking at the Eastern regions versus the West. Korea did not utilize it as much as the LPL but, perhaps due to the proximity of the regions and their willingness to scrim versus each other, definitely did utilize Renekton at a higher volume than LCS or LEC

My thoughts¶

The first thing that jumped out to me was the larger slice of the pie for nidalee in LCK in comparison to any other region, including LPL. This at first struck me as something that could be chalked up to the difference in volume of total games, surely LPL had to have been the region with the most nidalee's correct? What I ended up finding out when I dug deeper into the data was that LPL had 52 games on it and LCK 53, a fact that becomes even more remarkable when you consider the LPL nearly doubled LCK in terms of total games played. Surely this level of nidalee play in LCK had to factor into Canyon's impressive Nidalee at worlds, after all if he could dominate in the region that defined Nidalee play for Summer there wasn't much the world stage could throw at him that could hinder him. The fact that Lilia factored in heavily at worlds, and how she wasn't part of the meta game during summer long enough to crack the top five played for any region, without a doubt forced a large portion of teams to adjust their playstyle to the realities of the jungle pool at worlds. A great example of a specific Western team who had to go through this was G2, a team who even in their own worlds had to struggle in scrims in order to adjust to a completely different playstyle than the one they utilized during Summer 2020. After all in Europe none of Graves, Nidalee, Kindred cracked the top three most played jungle champions, and ultimately the reality of those lack of repetitions on the competitive stage forced them into a situation where they constantly were playing catchup.

My thoughts¶

One thing that comes as a bit of surprise was the fact that LCK was the only region that did not have Orianna, a long time staple, in their top 5 played during the regular season. Instead it seemed they heavily prioritized Sylas as a pick throughout the regular season. Despite that personally I doubt there would have been much trouble for them adapting to the worlds mid meta, as after all they might have broughten the deepest crop of mid laners, when compared to other regions, to worlds. Another interesting aspect that stood out to me was how underprioritized Zoe seemed to be at worlds, especially when compared to the regular season. Perhaps this was partially influenced by the carry jungle meta, as due to its ancillary effects the popularity of picks like Lucian shot up, as they synergized well with champs like Evelynn etc.

My thoughts¶

These graphs were actually the most interesting to look at becuase it felt like each region had their own unique prioritization of ADC's. LPL throughout their season clearly heavily utilized Aphelios, and then to a slightly lesser degree Ashe. If anything I think the large market share of those two champions goes far in terms of illustrating LPL as a bot centric region. I haven't looked at the specific games that underly this data as of now but if I was to hypothesize the large volume of ashe picks most likely began to come about upon the nerfing of Aphelios, which was clearly the tier one pick prior to said nerfs. This shows a high degree of prioritization, for the teams, in terms of ensuring that their ADC players end up utilizing the champion that has been shown to be tier one in their region.

As my eyes jumped to the other regions it became clear that they also had their own unique types of priorities on ADC's. Take LCK for an example, in comparison to LPL they had a far more equitable distribution of reliance across Aphelios, Ezreal, and Ashe. Furthermore when looking at LCS they had a whole different skew in their distribution of reliance, choosing to rely on Ashe and Ezreal at a higher rate than even the 200 year lord himself.

My thoughts¶

It was interesting to see the support prioritization that LCS went with. They were seemingly consistent with other regions, and the worlds meta, that they prioritized certain champs like Tahm Kench, Bard, and Nautilus throughout the season. However one thing that stands out in clear disparity with the rest of the world was their odd insistence on valuing champs like Rakan and Braum, which have their places in certain contexts within the meta of course, over one of the top support picks like Leona. Furthermore the lack of priority on Leona definitely stands in stark contrast with the moniker NAram that LCS has earned through their love of team fighting, surely a champ like Leona would fit right in!

Other than that nothing particularly stood out. There was the Pantheon pick that rose in popularity during worlds, however that was a consequence of meta shifts and innovation coming out of the LCK region. I do have to admit that Damwon gaming was probably helped by the heavy presence of Pantheon within the meta, as Beryl was one of the best supports in the world on it.

My Thoughts¶

What immediately jumped out about the summer seasons was the fact that LCS had the longest average game time of all the seasons. This makes sense with the narrative in my head as I seem to recall quite a few long drawn out NAram affairs throughout the regular season. Another funny thing that stuck out to me was how short their times were at worlds, though this could have come as a consequence of taking so many losses versus regions that beat them in a quicker manner. In comparison at worlds LEC dropped their average game time by around 2 minutes, while also managing to display an impressive level of success. This, in my eyes, indicates that they were forced to, and were willing to, adapt to the new meta that confronted them whilst facing the asian teams. This should stand as a testament to the mental strength that EU teams show every year going into worlds and successfully adapting, at least to a degree, to the asian meta.

My thoughts¶

Here what I was specifically looking to see was the tail of the distribution. From a bird's eye vie it becomes clear to me that in the LCK and LPL the distribution has more area under the curve towards the more extreme ends of the kda range than the LEC and LCS distributions do. In layman's terms what this essentially means is that there are more instances of top laner KDA's falling within a certain range, as an example perhaps in the 10-15 range, within the LCK and LPL regions than within LEC and LCS. If anything this tends to corroborate a stereotype that I have held in my head in regards to the difference between the presence and depth of carry top laners in the easter nregions versus the western regions. Furthermore if we were forced to stratify even more than there would be another layer of abstraction added to distinguish between the level of carry threat coming out of the top lane in EU than in NA, as the tail of the NA distribution looks embarassingly devoid of meat on the bone.

My thoughts¶

What I would like to posit is that perhaps this is reflective of the type of play of the region itself. People always claim that NA as a whole focuses too much on team fighting, mid lane, and lacks the proper side lane control and map movements that other regions consider fundamental to a good game of league of legends. What that increased fighting does, logically, is also lower KDA's as your chances of death would be higher.

Another thing that popped into my head looking at these graphs was that the LEC tail actually had a decent amount of instances. This goes to show the strength of the LEC marksman pool, something that unequivocally had taken a large step up this year thanks to the influx of mechanical talents such as Carzzy, Comp, Crownshot that served to bolster an already impressive pool consisting of players like Rekkles, Upset etc. This only bodes well for the level of ADC play that should be coming out of the LEC region in the upcoming days, the future only looks bright for LEC marksman.

First blood victims¶

In [291]:
def plotFirstBloodVictims(dftop, dfjng, dfmid, dfbot, dfsup):
    labels = ['TOP', 'JNG', 'MID', 'BOT', 'SUP']
    frequencies = [len(dftop[dftop['firstbloodvictim'] == 1]), len(dfjng[dfjng['firstbloodvictim'] == 1]), len(dfmid[dfmid['firstbloodvictim'] == 1]), len(dfbot[dfbot['firstbloodvictim'] == 1]), len(dfsup[dfsup['firstbloodvictim'] == 1]),]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.pie(frequencies, labels=labels, shadow=True, autopct = '%1.2f%%')
    plt.title("%s First Blood Victim %%" %(dftop.league.iloc[0]))
    plt.show()
In [292]:
plotFirstBloodVictims(lcs_top_data, lcs_jng_data, lcs_mid_data, lcs_bot_data, lcs_sup_data)
In [293]:
plotFirstBloodVictims(lpl_top_data, lpl_jng_data, lpl_mid_data, lpl_bot_data, lpl_sup_data)
In [294]:
plotFirstBloodVictims(lck_top_data, lck_jng_data, lck_mid_data, lck_bot_data, lck_sup_data)
In [295]:
plotFirstBloodVictims(lec_top_data, lec_jng_data, lec_mid_data, lec_bot_data, lec_sup_data)

My thoughts¶

Immediately I realized that top lane is truly a mans role. After all across all regions they are responsible for over 30% of the first bloods in every game, something that shouldn't come as too much of a surprise when you consider that they are the only individuals on the map playing solo in a long lane. From there what stood out ot me was how in LCK and LCS junglers were responsible for over 20% of the first bloods, while in LPL and LEC that over 20% allocation of first blood's actually fell on the shoulders of the supports. What I would posit as the reason for that in LEC and LPL is the strength of their ADC's. LPL has always historically had extremely strong mechanical talents coming out of the ADC role, after all they are the region that has given us names like Weixaoi, UZI, Namei, Jackeylove to name a few. Similarly the LEC marksman talent pool has actually, over the last few seasons of incremental progress, become arguably its strongest role (in competition with mid). When you look at the LEC marksman pool immediatley stud talents like Rekkles, Upset, Carzzy begin to illustrate the depth of talent within the region.

Gold Difference at 15 broken down by Role¶

Top¶

In [296]:

lck_top_data.golddiffat15.plot(title='LCK Top GD@15', kind='hist');
In [298]:

In [299]:
lcs_top_data.golddiffat15.plot(title='LCS Top GD@15', kind='hist');

My thoughts¶

Before starting off my soliloquy I would like to preface this be putting in the readers mind that all gold difference distributions will inherently look symmetric as whenever a player had a 1k gold lead over his enemy laner the enemy laner would have the same data point only in the negative. Now that I have established that premise I would like to point out the difference in the the ranges of the distribution across the regions. For LCS the maximum gold difference in the top lane at 15 minutes was only around 2500, which by itself is a respectable gold lead after all thats roughly one item. However when you compare that to to the other regions the disparity quickly jumps to the forefront. LPL and LEC both have had multiple instances of people geenrating over a 3k gold lead, and in the case of LCK, the preeminent home of some of the world's greatest top lane carry threats, some people have even managed to generate over a 4k gold lead. In my eyes this servers to show the difference in style of play as there has to be a concerted effort as a team in order to enable a top laner to carry. On the contrary some might point to a lack of top lane talent as being the reason for this, but in my eyes this can't be the primary factor as there actually is some quality top lane talent in North America (even if there original roots may have been in Korea).

My thoughts¶

In the case of the jungle distributions my eyes immediately jumped to the LEC distribution due to the limit in the ranges of said distributions. In the case of LEC the largest gold lead generated by the jungle position was just barely over 2k, whereas in the cases of other regions they managed to generate gold leads above or just around the 3k gold mark. While a 1k gold difference doesn't seem like much the disparity becomes clearer when you consider that the 15 minute mark leaves the game still in a mid game position. As such as the game goes farther on said disparity would only grow larger. In my eyes this ties into the statements that G2 made in regards to their experience at worlds, specifically how they maintained that they had to play catchup in regards to the carry jungle specific meta that was prevalent at worlds.

While I did comment on the LEC's distribution I would undoubtedly be remiss to ignore the LCS distribution. While the range of it seems to point to a carry jungle meta presence within the LCS something has to be said in regards to how thin the tail of the distribution actually is. The majority of the distribution seems to be centered around the 1500 range, which actually goes to show how the LCS was also not well adapted to the worlds meta going in. The style of play that the western regions were exhibiting was not akin to the style that was played by the asian regions throughout the season, and also the meta that ultimately came to dominate at worlds.

My thoughts¶

The LEC, LCK, and LPL distributions are actually pretty similar in regards to structure, the large differences, for example the thinner tail in the case of LEC, can largely be attributed to volume differences in terms of how many games were actually played by each league. However when you compare the LEC graph to the LCS graph there is a clear disparity in that the LCS tail is even skinnier than the LEC one. For some reason the style of play itself within the LCS region is far less conducive to high gold differences. One idea that could be posited to account for this difference could be the general passivity and the focus on team fights in the NA LCS region. While everyone does remark that the style of play in the LCS usually does come down to team fights, as opposed to other regions like LEC where general meta strategies like side laning also thrive, there actually are not as many skirmishes or team fights as there is in a region like LPL. In the case of LCS the region exhibits a tendency towards team fights in conjunction with a general level of passivity that, at least in my eyes, can inhibit truly large levels of gold leads from being generated.

My thoughts¶

At this point I feel like a broken clock that finds itself stuck at the same point chiming over and over again. In my case what I seem to be chiming in about is the tail of the LCS distribution, as a I feel that it constantly seems to be at lower ranges and generally skinnier than other regions. Furthermore I tend to find that the skinniness is at a level that can not be solely chalked up to the difference in volume of games played. As I type that I begin to consider that perhaps the difference in volume of games could play a larger role. Perhaps the fact that LCS players only get two chances to prove themselves a week leads them to inherently take on lower levels of risk and therefore cap the pop off potential that exists when you take on risk. However while this factor may be at play it can't be the only aspect affecting things due to the control group of LEC, which plays in a similar format but actually does not come with some of the inherent style of play limitations that the LCS does. Finally I do not believe in single factor analysis, one would be incredibly daft to orient their world view that way and as such I feel that the issues with LCS can only be accounted by a conjunction of various factors.

My thoughts¶

What I found really interesting about these gold shares was that the maximum value in certain roles tended to be in the regions that historically been renowned for those roles. Take for example LEC mids, historically Europe's strongest role, who happen to be given the largest proportionate share of the team gold when cross referenced with the mid laners of other regions. Similarly LCK has always been connoted with elite top lane carry threats, and as such it shouldn't come as a surprise that they rank nearly one percentage point higher in earned gold share than every other region. LPL also had its moment in the sun as they have the highest earned gold share for bot laners, though not that much higher than every other region which might simply be a consequence of the bot centric meta that was prevalent throughout most of summer.
